         <entryFree xml:id="k000144" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000144-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt" type="preferred">danbi</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000144-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">丹陛</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000144-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">丹陛</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000144-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">dānbì</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000144-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">tan-pi</term>
            <note type="Gloss">
               <p xml:lan="en" source="biblk000144-1">Danbi generally refers to the steps of palace buildings, sometimes the platform(月臺) in front of the building. It originated from steps chiseled out on the platform and painted with cinnabar(丹砂) in the Han Dynasty (202BCE-220CE) palaces. In the Ming and Qing Dynasties (1368-1911),danbi referred to the platform(月臺), which is related to danchi(丹墀).</p>
            </note>
